00:29:01.886 --> 00:29:04.286
So next we're going to look

00:29:04.286 --> 00:29:09.416
at this ad type called the IAB
Medium Rectangle Advertisement.

00:29:10.346 --> 00:29:12.286
So what is this?

00:29:12.286 --> 00:29:16.406
It's a view that's very similar
to a banner view, except instead

00:29:16.406 --> 00:29:18.496
of being positioned at the
bottom of your content,

00:29:18.496 --> 00:29:20.466
it's positioned in-line
with your content.

00:29:21.186 --> 00:29:24.586
The size of this
view is prescribed

00:29:24.666 --> 00:29:27.596
by the Interactive
Advertising Viewer,

00:29:27.626 --> 00:29:30.726
which is why it's called the
Medium Rectangle Advertisement.

00:29:30.726 --> 00:29:32.536
You might have seen
this on websites.

00:29:33.086 --> 00:29:36.306
It's 250 points by 300 points.

00:29:37.276 --> 00:29:40.336
It also has a similar cycling
behavior as the banner view,

00:29:40.336 --> 00:29:44.556
so as new ads become available,
the ad cycle in the view.

00:29:45.766 --> 00:29:49.446
And, again, like
the banner content,

00:29:49.856 --> 00:29:53.066
you also get full
screen ads on tap.

00:29:53.736 --> 00:29:56.636
This was introduced
in iOS 6 [inaudible],

00:29:56.636 --> 00:29:59.406
and it's available only on iPad.

00:29:59.936 --> 00:30:01.896
So how do we create
one of these things?

00:30:02.376 --> 00:30:04.496
As you noticed, it
was positioned in-line

00:30:04.846 --> 00:30:07.686
in the content, so you have
this greater flexibility

00:30:07.686 --> 00:30:10.706
and positioning of the
view within your content.

00:30:10.766 --> 00:30:15.076
So to do that, we need to
create this banner view

00:30:15.446 --> 00:30:17.366
of type medium rectangle.

00:30:17.796 --> 00:30:20.976
So here you can see after we've
imported the headers like we did

00:30:20.976 --> 00:30:23.806
for the banner view, we
created this new banner view

00:30:23.806 --> 00:30:25.546
of type medium rectangle.

00:30:25.956 --> 00:30:30.526
And this is going to create
nearly unloaded medium

00:30:30.526 --> 00:30:31.626
rectangle view.

00:30:32.606 --> 00:30:35.316
So we also need to configure
ourselves as the delegate

00:30:35.316 --> 00:30:38.146
of this view because
as ads become available

00:30:38.326 --> 00:30:43.376
and unavailable inside this
banner view, we need to be told

00:30:43.376 --> 00:30:45.916
so we know when to
present the view onscreen

00:30:46.006 --> 00:30:46.956
and take it off screen.

00:30:47.456 --> 00:30:49.006
So we set ourselves
as the delegate,

00:30:49.006 --> 00:30:51.706
and the protocol
that's used to talk

00:30:51.706 --> 00:30:54.996
to that delegate is the 80
Banner View Delegate protocol.

00:30:55.156 --> 00:30:57.816
So whichever object you've
assigned as the delegate needs

00:30:57.816 --> 00:31:00.366
to conform to the 80 Banner
View Delegate protocol.

00:31:00.696 --> 00:31:01.596
So we do that as well.

00:31:03.406 --> 00:31:05.356
When the banner is
ready to load,

00:31:05.426 --> 00:31:06.886
so we get this Delegate
Callback.

00:31:07.426 --> 00:31:10.126
That callback is called the
Banner View Did Load Callback.

00:31:10.426 --> 00:31:11.316
Called on the delegate.

00:31:12.086 --> 00:31:14.916
And when this happens,
that's an opportunity for you

00:31:14.916 --> 00:31:17.286
to present the ad on screen.

00:31:17.286 --> 00:31:21.016
We now have an ad
fulfilled by an ad request.

00:31:21.316 --> 00:31:23.096
We now need to turn
that into an impression.

00:31:23.906 --> 00:31:27.186
So to do that, you can do your
custom layout however you would

00:31:27.186 --> 00:31:29.326
like to present that view.

00:31:29.326 --> 00:31:32.926
You could cross-fade it in,
readjust your other views,

00:31:33.156 --> 00:31:36.146
and present that medium
rectangle ad in-line

00:31:36.146 --> 00:31:36.916
with your content.

00:31:39.496 --> 00:31:43.886
Similarly to banner ads, when
the medium rectangle is tapped,

00:31:44.136 --> 00:31:45.636
you get the full-screen ad.

00:31:46.316 --> 00:31:48.846
You also need to use
the view will disappear

00:31:48.846 --> 00:31:52.826
and view will appear callbacks
to pause any activity and sounds

00:31:52.826 --> 00:31:57.326
in your application to prevent
them clashing with any sounds

00:31:57.326 --> 00:32:01.126
and media that are
being played in the ad.

00:32:01.396 --> 00:32:04.406
When it comes time to unload
that medium rectangle,

00:32:04.816 --> 00:32:06.186
the next callback you'll receive

00:32:06.186 --> 00:32:09.586
on our Delegate is called the
bannerviewdidFailToReceiveAd

00:32:09.586 --> 00:32:10.846
with Error Callback.

00:32:11.536 --> 00:32:14.486
And this is an opportunity for
you to remove due to the reverse

00:32:14.586 --> 00:32:16.836
of adding the view to the
view hierarchy, and you want

00:32:16.836 --> 00:32:18.106
to move it off screen.

00:32:18.866 --> 00:32:20.126
It's important to
keep in mind here

00:32:20.126 --> 00:32:25.736
that you shouldn't just throw
away the medium rects ad view

00:32:26.186 --> 00:32:27.446
because you can just
keep it around.

00:32:27.446 --> 00:32:29.546
It'll continue to
cycle with new ads.

00:32:29.836 --> 00:32:32.576
So as those new ads
become available,

00:32:32.576 --> 00:32:36.636
you can simply add the same
medium rectangle ad view back

00:32:36.636 --> 00:32:38.496
to your views hierarchy.

00:32:40.176 --> 00:32:44.146
So much like banner
ads, we have some tools

00:32:44.146 --> 00:32:46.486
for testing medium rectangles.

00:32:46.926 --> 00:32:48.916
We still have the
adjustments to fill rate.

00:32:48.916 --> 00:32:50.746
They also work with
these medium recs.

00:32:51.126 --> 00:32:52.766
We have adjustments
to refresh rate.

00:32:52.986 --> 00:32:54.386
Same as we discussed before.

00:32:54.386 --> 00:32:59.216
But there's another additional
toggle that you can flip used

00:32:59.216 --> 00:33:02.446
for medium rectangles because
you're positioning them often

00:33:02.446 --> 00:33:04.666
in very specific ways
in line with content,

00:33:05.096 --> 00:33:09.316
and what that switch does is
it helps you avoid any clipping

00:33:09.316 --> 00:33:10.416
of that ad view.

00:33:10.946 --> 00:33:13.416
So we really want to
avoid clipping the ad view

00:33:13.416 --> 00:33:16.256
because that can prevent the
user from being able to see it

00:33:16.256 --> 00:33:17.566
or the user being
able to tap it,

00:33:17.706 --> 00:33:20.456
so by flipping the
highlight clipped banners,

00:33:20.766 --> 00:33:24.336
you get these overlaid
red or green views on top

00:33:24.336 --> 00:33:27.126
of your medium rects to show
whether it's being clipped

00:33:27.126 --> 00:33:27.406
or not.

00:33:27.726 --> 00:33:31.016
So make sure that you
run your application

00:33:31.016 --> 00:33:32.996
with this flag enabled
in Settings

00:33:33.266 --> 00:33:36.406
to make sure your medium
rects aren't being clipped.

00:33:37.236 --> 00:33:39.676
So let's get a demo of that.

00:33:40.506 --> 00:33:40.896
>> David Wilson: Okay.

00:33:41.296 --> 00:33:44.716
So to enter it medium rectangles

00:33:44.716 --> 00:33:49.326
into an application is a
little more complicated,

00:33:49.326 --> 00:33:50.246
as Nathan mentioned.

00:33:50.636 --> 00:33:52.966
So to do that, we're going to
start with a new application,

00:33:52.966 --> 00:33:55.646
and this is sort of a
bit of a game simulation.

00:33:56.236 --> 00:33:59.736
Most of the screen is going to
be taken up by the simulation.

00:33:59.736 --> 00:34:00.766
There's some text at the bottom

00:34:00.766 --> 00:34:03.756
that has some wasted white
space, and we're going to try

00:34:03.756 --> 00:34:05.426
to take advantage of
some of that white space,

00:34:05.426 --> 00:34:06.696
to include a medium rect

00:34:06.696 --> 00:34:08.456
in the bottom left
corner of our screen.

00:34:08.896 --> 00:34:12.025
Okay. So, anyway, you just
have to trust me that we have

00:34:12.025 --> 00:34:14.835
as a simulation at the top, and
we have some text at the bottom,

00:34:14.835 --> 00:34:18.045
and we've got a medium rectangle
that we're going to want to put

00:34:18.045 --> 00:34:19.846
on the bottom left
corner of the screen.

00:34:20.456 --> 00:34:23.896
So to do that, as we did
in our previous project,

00:34:23.896 --> 00:34:25.606
the first thing we're
going to need to do is link

00:34:25.606 --> 00:34:27.406
against the iAd framework.

00:34:27.696 --> 00:34:31.315
So click on our project
here, go over to Build Phases

00:34:31.315 --> 00:34:33.166
for the appropriate target.

00:34:33.166 --> 00:34:35.846
Link binary with Libraries.

00:34:35.846 --> 00:34:39.656
And we're going to link
in the iAd framework.

00:34:40.136 --> 00:34:42.926
Remember this is an
iPad only feature,

00:34:42.926 --> 00:34:46.606
so we can't actually demo
it with the iOS 7 STK today.

00:34:46.846 --> 00:34:51.356
But you can build applications
to run against iOS 6.1,

00:34:51.356 --> 00:34:54.396
and they will work with
the next seed for iOS 7.

00:34:55.146 --> 00:34:57.126
Once we've linked
against the iAd framework,

00:34:57.556 --> 00:35:00.526
the next thing we need to do
is go to our View Controller.

00:35:01.446 --> 00:35:03.616
We're going to go ahead and
Import the iAd framework here

00:35:03.616 --> 00:35:05.676
to give us access
to these API's.

00:35:06.496 --> 00:35:08.506
And because we need
to have a delegate

00:35:08.506 --> 00:35:10.676
for the medium rect banner view,

00:35:10.676 --> 00:35:12.596
we're going to make
our View Controller

00:35:12.706 --> 00:35:16.326
that 80 Banner View Delegate,
and then we're going to set

00:35:16.326 --> 00:35:21.266
up a couple properties to hold
the new 80 Banner View Medium

00:35:21.266 --> 00:35:24.216
Rect that we're going to create,
and to keep track of whether

00:35:24.216 --> 00:35:26.396
or not the ad is
currently visible on screen.

00:35:26.756 --> 00:35:29.046
We're going to need this so that
we can do the appropriate layout

00:35:29.046 --> 00:35:31.656
as the banner view
loads and unloads.

00:35:32.466 --> 00:35:35.926
So once we have those
properties inside Load View,

00:35:35.926 --> 00:35:39.156
we can go ahead and
instantiate that.

00:35:39.666 --> 00:35:41.946
Note that all we have to
do is alloc initWithAd:

00:35:42.076 --> 00:35:45.146
ADAdTypeMediumRectangle,
and then remember

00:35:45.146 --> 00:35:48.216
to set the delegate to
the View Controller.

00:35:49.056 --> 00:35:50.776
Once we've done that, we need

00:35:50.776 --> 00:35:53.526
to update our
viewDidLayoutSubviews method

00:35:53.526 --> 00:35:56.486
so that we can include the
medium rect inside our layout.

00:35:57.316 --> 00:36:01.526
So all we need to do here is
do some frame calculations

00:36:01.526 --> 00:36:03.136
for the medium rect,
which puts it,

00:36:03.936 --> 00:36:06.446
with the calculations
here we're doing is layout

00:36:06.446 --> 00:36:09.016
out the medium rect in the
bottom left of the screen

00:36:09.016 --> 00:36:11.226
if it's loaded, and
just off-screen

00:36:11.226 --> 00:36:13.066
in the bottom left,
if it's not loaded.

00:36:13.416 --> 00:36:16.636
That allows us to do smooth
animated transitions on

00:36:16.636 --> 00:36:19.046
and off screen, as
the loaded property

00:36:19.046 --> 00:36:20.416
of this banner view changes.

00:36:20.856 --> 00:36:23.676
To do that, we're also going
to need to adjust the origin

00:36:23.676 --> 00:36:25.066
of the frame that's next to it.

00:36:25.206 --> 00:36:27.816
Once we've done that,
then we need

00:36:27.816 --> 00:36:30.656
to actually start implementing
the delegate method callbacks

00:36:30.656 --> 00:36:33.236
that will tell us when things
happen with this banner view.

00:36:33.976 --> 00:36:37.066
So the first thing we're going
to do is go down to the bottom

00:36:37.616 --> 00:36:40.516
and hide the rest of this.

00:36:40.686 --> 00:36:43.366
Then we go to first start

00:36:43.366 --> 00:36:46.186
out by implementing
bannerViewDidLoadAd.

00:36:46.286 --> 00:36:50.296
This is our cue to move
the banner onscreen

00:36:50.406 --> 00:36:51.736
if it's not already there.

00:36:52.256 --> 00:36:55.396
This is iAd telling us that
there's a new ad that's in place

00:36:55.396 --> 00:36:57.196
in the view and we should
display it to the user.

00:36:58.016 --> 00:36:59.376
If it's already visible,
that's fine.

00:36:59.376 --> 00:37:01.226
We don't need to
take any action.

00:37:01.226 --> 00:37:03.636
If it's not, we're going
to set our property here

00:37:03.636 --> 00:37:06.316
and then we're just going
to do a quick animation

00:37:06.316 --> 00:37:09.556
to move this thing onscreen by
just calling setNeedsLayout,

00:37:09.816 --> 00:37:12.286
layoutIfNeeded, and letting
the layout code that we did

00:37:12.286 --> 00:37:14.096
up above handle this for us.

00:37:15.176 --> 00:37:17.316
Now once the banner's been
onscreen for a little while,

00:37:17.316 --> 00:37:20.336
we're going to have to move it
back off screen if it unloads,

00:37:20.936 --> 00:37:23.296
say the user moves out
of network connectivity,

00:37:23.296 --> 00:37:25.176
or we just run out of inventory.

00:37:25.266 --> 00:37:26.746
So we're going to implement

00:37:26.746 --> 00:37:29.276
in this case the
bannerViewDidFailToLoadAd

00:37:29.276 --> 00:37:30.776
with error method.

00:37:30.776 --> 00:37:34.276
This is almost identical
to moving it onscreen,

00:37:34.276 --> 00:37:36.346
except we're going to
change our property to No,

00:37:37.016 --> 00:37:39.626
and then we're going to
again do an animation based

00:37:39.626 --> 00:37:41.786
on setNeedsLayout,
layoutIfNeeded.

00:37:42.196 --> 00:37:44.506
So that'll move the
thing on and off screen,

00:37:44.506 --> 00:37:46.306
but there's one more thing
we need to take care of,

00:37:46.306 --> 00:37:47.986
and that's pausing our game

00:37:47.986 --> 00:37:49.886
when the user actually
interacts with this ad.

00:37:50.196 --> 00:37:51.506
We've got a simulation running.

00:37:51.506 --> 00:37:52.776
It's taking up CPU.

00:37:53.046 --> 00:37:54.876
Maybe the user is actually
interested in watching

00:37:54.876 --> 00:37:57.236
that simulation, and we
don't want to let it just go

00:37:57.236 --> 00:38:00.606
on behind the scenes while the
user's interacting with the ad.

00:38:01.226 --> 00:38:02.636
So to do that, we're
going to go ahead

00:38:02.636 --> 00:38:05.496
and implement view did
appear, view did disappear

00:38:05.496 --> 00:38:08.466
on our view controller, and
all we need to do here is start

00:38:08.466 --> 00:38:11.066
and stop timers that are
running our simulation.

00:38:11.066 --> 00:38:14.136
If you had media, this would
also be your cure to pause

00:38:14.136 --> 00:38:15.506
and then resume the media.

00:38:16.196 --> 00:38:17.356
Once we've done that,

00:38:17.806 --> 00:38:19.856
if our demo machine were
working we could run it again,

00:38:20.076 --> 00:38:22.636
but that's pretty much
all you need to do

00:38:22.636 --> 00:38:25.056
to get medium rects
integrated into your app.

00:38:25.656 --> 00:38:27.126
And with that I'll
bring Nathan back out.

00:38:27.306 --> 00:38:29.626
>> Nathan de Vries: So the next
ad type which we're excited

00:38:29.626 --> 00:38:32.576
to talk about today, is
the pre-roll video ad.

00:38:32.856 --> 00:38:36.006
We've had a lot of requests for
this, and it's new to iOS 7,

00:38:36.506 --> 00:38:39.586
and what this lets you do
is integrate seamlessly

00:38:39.586 --> 00:38:41.276
with the media player API's

00:38:41.506 --> 00:38:45.616
to request playback all the
video before your video content.

00:38:46.376 --> 00:38:48.586
So as I said, it's
brand new in iOS 7.

00:38:49.136 --> 00:38:52.036
It's integrated with
the media player API's.

00:38:52.036 --> 00:38:54.486
So the way you would
normally play back media

00:38:54.486 --> 00:38:56.476
with the MP movie
player controller API,

00:38:57.076 --> 00:38:59.286
you can now just
use a different API

00:38:59.406 --> 00:39:03.576
to play a pre-roll
ad before that media.

00:39:03.786 --> 00:39:05.426
When the pre-roll
starts playing,

00:39:05.716 --> 00:39:08.846
this happens before the
media content starts playing,

00:39:08.926 --> 00:39:11.826
your primary media
content starts playing,

00:39:12.216 --> 00:39:13.916
and when the advertisement
finishes,

00:39:14.216 --> 00:39:17.406
you get this seamless transition
to the main content video.

00:39:18.056 --> 00:39:21.736
If the user engages with the
video while it's displayed

00:39:21.736 --> 00:39:22.846
with this pre-roll video,

00:39:23.196 --> 00:39:26.356
they get that standard
full-screen immersive ad

00:39:26.356 --> 00:39:27.546
experience as well.

00:39:27.546 --> 00:39:29.816
Just like all of the other
advertisements we support.

00:39:30.856 --> 00:39:33.186
We also support Inline playback.

00:39:33.376 --> 00:39:34.656
So if you've got an application

00:39:34.656 --> 00:39:37.716
that doesn't assume
full-screen media playback,

00:39:38.036 --> 00:39:40.776
then you can also use
pre-roll video in that scenario

00:39:40.776 --> 00:39:43.556
by using the embedded style
for MP movie player controller,

00:39:43.556 --> 00:39:47.676
and this is supported
on both iPhone and iPad.

00:39:48.156 --> 00:39:50.806
So let's take a look
at how to create one

00:39:50.806 --> 00:39:52.626
of these MP movie
player controllers.

00:39:53.506 --> 00:39:56.436
In addition to the usual iAd
framework import that you need

00:39:56.436 --> 00:39:57.826
to do for the other ad types,

00:39:58.236 --> 00:40:00.516
the MP movie player
controller functionality is

00:40:00.516 --> 00:40:03.006
in the media player framework.

00:40:03.276 --> 00:40:04.756
So you'll need to
link media player

00:40:05.216 --> 00:40:07.576
and also import the
media player headers.

00:40:09.086 --> 00:40:11.906
We then need to create a new
MP movie player controller,

00:40:12.116 --> 00:40:14.106
or an MP movie player
view controller,

00:40:14.196 --> 00:40:17.516
depending on your application,
and set the content URL

00:40:17.706 --> 00:40:19.176
of that movie player controller.

00:40:19.526 --> 00:40:21.416
This is the usual video content

00:40:21.416 --> 00:40:23.296
that you would have been
playing before you started

00:40:23.296 --> 00:40:24.576
integrating iAd.

00:40:24.756 --> 00:40:28.046
After we've done that, instead
of calling the play method

00:40:28.046 --> 00:40:29.506
on the movie player controller,

00:40:29.756 --> 00:40:33.456
iAd has this new category
method called playPrerollAdWith

00:40:33.456 --> 00:40:35.406
CompletionHandler,
which allows you

00:40:35.406 --> 00:40:37.916
to provide a completion
block that gets called

00:40:38.136 --> 00:40:41.726
after the ad finishes, or if
there was no other ad available

00:40:41.726 --> 00:40:44.606
at the time of requesting
a pre-roll ad.

00:40:44.786 --> 00:40:47.646
Once you've called this API,
you can immediately add,

00:40:48.126 --> 00:40:52.676
so inside that handler, once
the playback has finished,

00:40:52.856 --> 00:40:54.916
or if there wasn't a
pre-roll available,

00:40:55.366 --> 00:40:57.896
that's your opportunity
to call the play API

00:40:57.896 --> 00:41:01.826
and play your original
video content.

00:41:03.426 --> 00:41:04.936
Once you've called
this Play Pre-Roll Ad

00:41:04.936 --> 00:41:06.236
with Completion Handler API,

00:41:06.786 --> 00:41:09.066
you can then add the movie
player controllers view

00:41:09.096 --> 00:41:10.266
to your view hierarchy,

00:41:10.566 --> 00:41:13.166
or you can present the
movie player view controller

00:41:13.376 --> 00:41:14.466
in your application.

00:41:15.076 --> 00:41:19.226
If you've got an app that has
a scenario where you would

00:41:19.226 --> 00:41:22.136
like to conditionally play
pre-roll for some users

00:41:22.166 --> 00:41:25.426
and not others, or maybe you've
got some time based logic as to

00:41:25.426 --> 00:41:28.806
when you want to show pre-roll
ads, you can do that too.

00:41:29.316 --> 00:41:32.706
All you need to do is
call the play API instead

00:41:32.706 --> 00:41:36.236
of calling the Play Pre-Roll
Ad with Completion Handler API.

00:41:36.236 --> 00:41:38.966
And you can come up with your
own logic for when you do

00:41:38.966 --> 00:41:40.726
and you don't, display
pre-roll ads,

00:41:40.776 --> 00:41:44.566
and which situations are
optimal for your app.

00:41:46.056 --> 00:41:49.136
Much like interstitial ads,
you also need to prepare early.

00:41:49.206 --> 00:41:50.696
You need to tell
the ad framework

00:41:50.696 --> 00:41:53.006
that it should start
sending requests as soon

00:41:53.006 --> 00:41:55.586
as the application launches,
so that the first time

00:41:55.586 --> 00:41:57.086
that a user taps on a video,

00:41:57.416 --> 00:42:00.046
a pre-roll ad is more
likely to be available.

00:42:00.546 --> 00:42:02.856
It's all about not missing
those early impressions.

00:42:03.396 --> 00:42:05.806
So similarly to the
UI view controller,

00:42:05.806 --> 00:42:07.446
preparing [inaudible]
ads called,

00:42:08.076 --> 00:42:13.376
we now swap that with an MP
movie player controller prepare

00:42:13.376 --> 00:42:14.626
pre-roll ads [inaudible].

00:42:14.716 --> 00:42:16.676
And this will do the
same effective thing.

00:42:16.676 --> 00:42:18.356
It's sending off
ad requests as soon

00:42:18.356 --> 00:42:20.706
as your application
becomes available.

00:42:21.326 --> 00:42:25.626
So there are a couple of gotchas

00:42:25.626 --> 00:42:28.166
with the movie player
controller API.

00:42:28.916 --> 00:42:32.046
Those of you that are already
using MP movie player controller

00:42:32.046 --> 00:42:34.456
will need to keep in
mind that you may need

00:42:34.456 --> 00:42:37.546
to adjust your application
to accommodate pre-roll ads.

00:42:38.516 --> 00:42:40.826
The first thing that you
need to make sure of is

00:42:40.826 --> 00:42:45.026
that if you're ever explicitly
playing your MP movie player

00:42:45.426 --> 00:42:48.166
controller, you need to make
sure that that doesn't happen

00:42:48.166 --> 00:42:50.046
until the completion
handler is pulled.

00:42:50.536 --> 00:42:54.106
This is because it's the main
content starts playing while the

00:42:54.106 --> 00:42:54.936
pre-roll is playing,

00:42:55.196 --> 00:42:57.406
we'll immediately skip
to the main content.

00:42:57.996 --> 00:42:59.376
So bear that in mind.

00:42:59.906 --> 00:43:02.686
There's two slightly indirect
times that this can happen.

00:43:03.056 --> 00:43:06.756
Many people will observe
these two notifications

00:43:06.756 --> 00:43:10.096
on MP movie player controller,
when the video becomes available

00:43:10.096 --> 00:43:12.496
for playback, and also
when the first frame

00:43:12.496 --> 00:43:14.406
of the video is available
for display.

00:43:15.066 --> 00:43:18.146
A lot of developers use
these and rightly so,

00:43:18.146 --> 00:43:20.446
for playing back the media
content, but you need

00:43:20.446 --> 00:43:23.006
to be aware that if you
call play in response

00:43:23.006 --> 00:43:26.656
to these notifications, you
may skip the pre-roll adds,

00:43:26.656 --> 00:43:28.826
so make sure that you don't
handle these notifications

00:43:28.826 --> 00:43:33.646
until after the callback
handler is called, and likewise

00:43:33.646 --> 00:43:35.196
if your customizing the UI

00:43:35.196 --> 00:43:37.746
of the MP movie player
controller, which is supported.

00:43:37.746 --> 00:43:42.396
You also need to hold off on
inserting any custom views

00:43:42.396 --> 00:43:45.196
into the view controller's
view until after

00:43:45.196 --> 00:43:46.676
that completion handler
is called

00:43:46.736 --> 00:43:50.186
because you don't want your
views colliding with any

00:43:50.186 --> 00:43:51.216
of the pre-roll content.

